.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1423:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/003-wave-executor/scratch/codex-gpt54-deep-research.md:4247:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/003-wave-executor/spec.md:43:**Phase Context**: This phase adds orchestrator-managed parallel batches on top of the coverage-graph substrate from Phase 002. The goal is scale without architectural drift: the workers stay LEAF, while orchestration logic handles segmentation, fan-out, pruning, promotion, and merge.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1424:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/003-wave-executor/scratch/codex-gpt54-deep-research.md:4704:6. **Convergence per segment**. Focus: whether each segment needs its own graph/coverage instance. Findings: convergence docs already say segment filtering should apply only to the current segment while hard stops still count all iterations and cross-segment analysis still reads the full JSONL ([convergence.md:23](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/convergence.md#L23), [convergence.md:305](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/convergence.md#L305)); the workers already expect the orchestrator to add `segment` and `convergenceSignals` to iteration records ([deep-research.md:189](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-research.md#L189), [deep-review.md:253](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-review.md#L253)); review STOP is explicitly global because it depends on total P0/P1 counts, full-dimension coverage, and global quality gates ([spec_kit_deep-review_auto.yaml:340](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/spec_kit/assets/spec_kit_deep-review_auto.yaml#L340)). Novel insight: one global coverage graph plus segment-scoped queries is cleaner than spinning up a separate graph per segment. Open question: how should unresolved nodes from retired segments contribute to the final global stop-decision trace?
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1425:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/003-wave-executor/scratch/codex-gpt54-deep-research.md:4752:6. **Convergence per segment**. Focus: whether each segment needs its own graph/coverage instance. Findings: convergence docs already say segment filtering should apply only to the current segment while hard stops still count all iterations and cross-segment analysis still reads the full JSONL ([convergence.md:23](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/convergence.md#L23), [convergence.md:305](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-deep-research/references/convergence.md#L305)); the workers already expect the orchestrator to add `segment` and `convergenceSignals` to iteration records ([deep-research.md:189](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-research.md#L189), [deep-review.md:253](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/agents/deep-review.md#L253)); review STOP is explicitly global because it depends on total P0/P1 counts, full-dimension coverage, and global quality gates ([spec_kit_deep-review_auto.yaml:340](/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/commands/spec_kit/assets/spec_kit_deep-review_auto.yaml#L340)). Novel insight: one global coverage graph plus segment-scoped queries is cleaner than spinning up a separate graph per segment. Open question: how should unresolved nodes from retired segments contribute to the final global stop-decision trace?
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1426:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/archive-rvw-2026-04-11/iterations/iteration-003.md:4:This pass stayed on security around graph identity generation and cross-session reuse, then rotated into traceability and maintainability on the visible confirm/reference mirrors. I reviewed the coverage-graph upsert path, the confirm YAML graphEvents transforms, and the published state-format references to see whether the session namespace is encoded in the live contract or only carried as an out-of-band parameter.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1427:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/archive-rvw-2026-04-11/iterations/iteration-003.md:37:- In-memory `coverage-graph-core.cjs` edge auto-ID generation: not on the visible deep-loop write path for this bundle — live research/review graph persistence goes through `deep_loop_graph_upsert` from the confirm/auto YAMLs, not through `insertEdge()` in the in-memory helper.
.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/z_archive/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/iterations/iteration-008.md:1428:.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/042-sk-deep-research-review-improvement-2/review/archive-rvw-2026-04-11/iterations/iteration-003.md:40:- Looking for a second handler-side auth or validation bypass in `mcp_server/handlers/coverage-graph/upsert.ts`: the handler validates `specFolder`, `loopType`, `sessionId`, relation/kind enums, and self-loops, so this pass did not uncover a new security defect there beyond the pre-existing bare-ID storage semantics already captured in F004.
